  "market_context": "NQ1! 5-minute chart on November 27, 2023. After the open, price formed an initial intraday range. The analyst uses this live example to demonstrate how the internal-to-external range liquidity cycle applies fractally on lower intraday timeframes, not just on higher timeframes.",
  "key_observation": "Price cyclically oscillates between external range liquidity (swing highs/lows of the opening range) and internal range liquidity (fair value gaps formed within the range). After taking one form of liquidity, price retraces to the opposite form before continuing.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identify the initial range created by the open on the NQ 5-minute chart and wait for one side of the range to be taken.",
    "Step 2: Observe an aggressive move out of the range and back into it, then anticipate a retracement from external to internal range liquidity.",
    "Step 3: Note that after retracing to internal, price should target external again — confirmed when a new high was made.",
    "Step 4: After taking external (the new high) with no fair value gap present, wait for the next internal level — identify a newly formed fair value gap as the new internal liquidity.",
    "Step 5: Confirm that price respects the internal fair value gap, then anticipate movement back to external liquidity.",
    "Step 6: Observe external being taken again, then watch for another fair value gap to form as new internal liquidity, continuing the external→internal→external cycle."
  ],
  "outcome": null,
  "lessons": "The internal-to-external range liquidity model is fractal and applies on any timeframe, including intraday 5-minute charts. Once one side is taken, anticipate the opposite type of liquidity as the next draw — external sweeps lead to internal FVG retracements, which then lead to new external targets.",
